mies and critics as imperial power ran its course? Lincoln shows how these religious ideas shaped Achaemenian practice and brought the Persians unprecedented wealth, power, and territory, but also produced unmanageable contradictions, as in a gruesome case of torture discussed in the book’s final chapter. Close study of that episode leads Lincoln back to the present with a postscript that provides a searing and utterly novel perspective on the photographs from Abu Ghraib.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aReligion and politicszIranvCase studies. 0aReligion and politics. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aachaemenian persia, abu ghraib, religion, empire, imperialism, violence, government, ambition, conquest, invasion, territory, expansion, theology, iran, middle east, dynasty, nonfiction, history, dualism, ethics, divine election, mission, salvation, cosmos, morality, paradise lost, wealth, power, torture, politics, purpose, land rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022648196840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226481913423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226481913/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles